	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>ESADA calls for rapid progress in removing non-tariff barriers to dairy trade in ESA region </h1>

			
			<h4>
												15 July 2013
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>According to press reports, the Eastern and Southern African Dairy Association (ESADA) has called on COMESA governments “to remove non-tariff barriers that are hindering the growth of the dairy sector in the region.” ESADA called on member state governments to “harmonize the standards laws and allow flexible import and export of dairy products within the region”, since currently COMESA members were trading more with European countries than with each other in the ESADA region. According to the Association, 90% (by value) of dairy trade takes place with countries outside the COMESA region and only 10% between COMESA members.</p><p>ESADA’s CEO, Peter Ngaruiya, called for standards to be harmonised within a year to a level acceptable across the region. However, he recognised that in Southern Africa “quality standards are extremely high”, which posed challenges for Eastern African dairy producers. He also noted that sometimes standards were high but “not backed by science”, implying that in some instances the standards were protectionist in intent. In this context, he asserted the safety of Eastern African dairy products.</p><p>In Uganda, according to a government minister speaking at a Dairy Development Authority awards presentation on ‘Quality commitment and achievement’, local milk production continues to grow at a rate of 8–10% per annum. The Animal Industries and Fisheries Minister said that currently 70% of production was commercially marketed and 30% consumed directly by farming households. The value of commercially marketed milk was estimated at US$514.3 million in 2012, up from US$338.1 million in 2011 (+32.5%). This has led to a decrease in the value of milk imports from US$1.9 million in 2011 to US$1.4 million in 2012 (–26.3%). Meanwhile, Uganda is exporting UHT milk, ghee, cheese and milk powder to neighbouring East African countries: the value of its dairy sector exports increased from US$3.4 million in 2011 to US$11.5 million in 2012 (+228%).</p><p>Dairy sector development is accorded a high priority by the Ugandan government, since approximately 26% of households own cattle and hence could potentially benefit from an expansion of production and commercial processing of milk. This needs to be seen against the background of warnings from the government regarding the safety of unprocessed milk. The government is actively encouraging the consumption of packaged milk, where products have been subjected to safety checks. Currently, according to press reports, of the 1.8 billion litres of milk consumed each year, 90% is marketed as unprocessed milk, which is generally cheaper. According to government sources, “Uganda's capacity to process milk had increased to one million litres of milk per day”, with the network of cooling facilities being increased to 900 litres/day. It estimated that currently milk to the value of USh50 billion per annum is being lost due to milk spoilage.</p><p>According to Kenyan press sources, Kenya is also looking to increase commercial processing of camel milk, for which major export opportunities are seen in Asia and the Gulf.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
