<a href="http://www.businessdailyafrica.com/Corporate-News/Camel-milk-exporters-eye-Asia--UAE-markets-/-/539550/1867582/-/xndet2z/-/index.html " target="_self">http://www.businessdailyafrica.com/Corporate-News/Camel-milk-exporters-e...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Non-tariff barriers (NTBs) to trade are just one impediment to expanding intra-COMESA trade in dairy products. More fundamental challenges arise from relatively low product quality, the limited product range and an associated consumer preference for high-quality products from the developed world. The reliability and continuity of supply from developed country suppliers also finds favour with importers, a situation compounded by infrastructure constraints on intra-regional trade, which can delay deliveries and increase the costs of regionally sourced products. Important issues of cost competitiveness, linked to feed costs and productivity, also need to be addressed.</p><p>It is against this broader background that the issue of divergent national standards for dairy products, as well as the use of food safety, SPS and general standards, needs to be seen.</p><p>Harmonising SPS and quality standards is unlikely to be a straightforward task. Simply transposing international standards would be likely to leave many dairy processing companies in the region (apart from in South Africa and Namibia) unable to meet the new standards (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Commodities/Dairy/Initiatives-to-establish-an-EAC-regional-dairy-development-strategy" target="_blank">Initiatives to establish an EAC regional dairy development strategy</a>’, 6 October 2011). This raises the question of which production standards should then be used for harmonisation purposes, with different standards favouring different national producers or even different types of national producer (i.e. commercial dairy farmers rather than small-scale producers), carrying significant implications for national rural development strategies. With growing regional and international interest in Eastern African dairy sector development, the future standards to be applied could also carry important implications for patterns of future investment.</p><p>Representative stakeholder bodies will need to play an active role in standards harmonisation processes, including in the formulation of regional arbitration mechanisms for dealing with disputes related to SPS, food safety and quality standards. However, this needs to be part of a wider regional dairy sector development strategy, taking into account changing global trade and investment patterns.</p><p>A more holistic approach is therefore required if intra-COMESA trade in dairy products is to improve.</p>
		</div>
		
